    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2570679582" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2570679582" />
    <a title="C" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/50979407-c"><img alt="C" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2570679582?book_show_action=true">Dec 13, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="C" class="user" itemprop="url" name="C" href="/user/show/50979407-c">C</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2570679582" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18333693890146790498">&quot;Poland&quot; is an epic historical novel tracing the intertwined lives of three fictional families throughout 700+ years of real Polish history.<br/><br/>The novel is bookended with a fictional conflict between members of two of these families, set in the waning days of Communist Poland (the book was published in 1982, so this was &quot;modern day&quot; at the time): Janko Buk is working to unionize Polish farmers and the government has dispatched Szymon Bukowski to the town of Bukowo to dissuade him.<br/><br/>After an introduct</span>
  <span id="freeText18333693890146790498" style="display:none">"Poland" is an epic historical novel tracing the intertwined lives of three fictional families throughout 700+ years of real Polish history.<br /><br />The novel is bookended with a fictional conflict between members of two of these families, set in the waning days of Communist Poland (the book was published in 1982, so this was "modern day" at the time): Janko Buk is working to unionize Polish farmers and the government has dispatched Szymon Bukowski to the town of Bukowo to dissuade him.<br /><br />After an introduction to these two characters, we rewind to the Mongol invasions of Poland in the 1200s. Subsequent chapters follow invasions by the Teutonic Knights, Swedes and Ottomans, taking us to the late 1600s. The chapters track different members of the peasant Buk family, lesser noble Bukowskis, and greater noble Lubonskis, all who live in and around the fictional town of Bukowo.<br /><br />I found Michener to be a solid writer of battles, and the historical battles are portrayed with both suspense and clarity. Even though most characters only appear in one chapter (the chapters generally being separated by dozens or hundreds of years), there's often continuity in the characteristics of different members of the same family. More importantly, Poland and its people are portrayed as a character onto their own, and this characterization spans the whole book.<br /><br />Unfortunately, the book starts to get a little bogged down. An interesting portrayal of the incredibly dysfunctional Polish politics of the 1700s (justified by Poles as "The Golden Freedom," in which any one nobleman can veto actions of the entire legislature, and foreign kings are elected so that that they don't get too strong) morphs into a tremendously dull tour of the country as noble characters look for a suitable marriage. It does end on a strong note, with a failed rebellion led by a Polish general who fought in the American Revolution.<br /><br />Fast forward a hundred years, when Poland has temporarily ceased to exist. Do you like Chopin? I sure hope so, because you'll be treated to pages upon pages of textual descriptions of his compositions, set against the backdrop of a forbidden romance and the desire for a free Poland. This is where the lack of strong individual characters really starts to show, because while the book has invested you in Poland as a whole, it sure hasn't invested you in the romantic pursuits of its somewhat flat characters. The following chapter, set after World War I, is similarly dull but ends with a return to form depicting conflicts between Poland and the newly founded Soviet Union.<br /><br />The penultimate chapter is a depiction of Nazi-occupied Poland. While the European theater of WWII is probably the most overdone era in modern Western historical fiction, I found Michener's take on the Majdanek concentration camp and the Polish resistance to be both gripping and haunting. We're also re-introduced to Szymon Bukowski, portrayed as a soulless Communist bureaucrat in the first chapter but given significantly more backstory here.<br /><br />The final chapter returns us to the story in 1981, and while I appreciated the new angle at which I was able to view Szymon's character, the story dragged on a bit much and become a little too heavy-handed, with the resolution being somewhat unfulfilling to me.<br /><br />In short, the book alternates between near-greatness and near-deadening mediocrity. The lack of individual strong characters detaches the reader from their individual storylines; since "Poland" is the only consistent character, the book seems strongest when the fate of the nation is at stake, and weakest when the individual characters' interests and ambitions are highlighted.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18333693890146790498" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


